    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1923-12-17T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1923-12-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="440"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d440">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.48B/345</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-12-17">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 17, 1923</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[Received January 7, 1924.]</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 141–E</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to my despatch No. 132–E of
                    December 14, 1923,<note n="40" xml:id="d440fn40">Not printed.</note> regarding
                    the recent earthquake disaster, I have the honor to report that the Home Office
                    now announces that the number of houses directly destroyed by the earthquake in
                    the devastated area was 134,963, while the number of houses destroyed by fire in
                    that <pb facs="0619" n="495" xml:id="pg_495"/> region was 444,576. At the same
                    time, 794 houses were destroyed by landslides and tidal waves.</p>
                <p>The number killed in the entire area was 144,720; injured, 102,409; missing,
                    50,601.</p>
                <p>Of the killed in Tokyo, 33,000 (19,566 men, 24,425 women) were above 50 years of
                    age; 28,364 (21,300 men, 7,064 women), between 30 and 40 years; 30,616, between
                    3 and 10 years; and 8,020, of unknown age.</p>
                <p>The figures for the injured in Tokyo are also interesting, showing that 18,253
                    (8,200 boys, 10,058 girls) were between 5 and 10 years; and over 20,047 (13,854
                    men, 7,893 women) were above 50 years.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Jefferson Caffery</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
